    "text": "Erdős Problem #387: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Is there an absolute constant $c>0$ such that, for all $1\\leq k< n$, the binomial coefficient $\\binom{n}{k}$ has a divisor in $(cn,n]$? Current best: Faulkner \\cite{Fa66} proved that, if $p$ is the least prime $>2k$ and $n\\geq p$, then $\\binom{n}{k}$ has a prime divisor $\\geq p$ (except $\\binom{9}{2}$ and $\\binom{10}{3}$). Prize: no. Tags: binomial coefficients, number theory.",
